    answer: 'Arabia before the Prophet\'s ﷺ birth was in a state the Quran describes as evident misguidance. Religiously: the original Abrahamic monotheism of Ibrahim and Isma\'il had been corrupted over centuries. The Ka\'bah, originally built for the worship of Allah alone, had been filled with 360 idols. Polytheism (shirk) was the dominant religion — each tribe had patron deities, and the Quraysh served as custodians of the idols. Belief in jinns, divination (kahanah), and astrology was widespread. A small minority — the Hunafa\' like Waraqah ibn Nawfal and Zayd ibn Amr ibn Nufayl — maintained traces of Abrahamic monotheism. Socially: the tribe was the supreme social unit — loyalty was to tribe above all. Tribal warfare was endemic — the War of Basus lasted 40 years. Women were property: infanticide of daughters was practised by some tribes. Social stratification was rigid: the Quraysh aristocracy controlled trade and the sanctuary. Economically: Makkah was a prosperous trading hub on the incense route between Yemen and the Levant, and the Quraysh\'s control of the Haram gave them significant commercial power.',
