    answer: 'The Prophet\'s ﷺ dawah methodology had two distinct phases: Makkan Phase (13 years — years 1-13 of prophethood): characterized by (1) Sirriyyah (secrecy) for the first three years — individual outreach to those closest to him; (2) Jahri (open) dawah from year 4 — public proclamation, direct confrontation of shirk, Quranic recitation; (3) Focus on tawhid and akhirah — the vast majority of Makkan Quran deals with Allah\'s existence, attributes, and the Day of Judgment; (4) Sabr (patience) under persecution — no armed resistance; (5) Use of the pilgrimage season to reach tribes visiting Makkah. Madinan Phase (10 years — years 1-10 AH): characterized by (1) Community building — mosque, brotherhood, constitution; (2) Legislation — Madinan Quran contains the social, legal, and economic laws; (3) Diplomacy — letters to kings, treaties with tribes; (4) Military — defense, then deterrence, then expansion; (5) Institutional development — zakah collection, judiciary, governance. The wisdom of the phased approach: dawah without power requires patience and character; power without dawah foundation lacks legitimacy and sustainability. The Makkan period built the human capital; the Madinan period built the institution. Scholars of dawah methodology (manhaj ad-dawah) study this phased approach as the model for Islamic renewal.',
