    answer: 'Usul Al-Fiqh (the Principles of Islamic Jurisprudence) is the science that establishes the methods, sources, and rules by which Islamic legal rulings (ahkam) are derived from their evidences (adillah). Imam Ash-Shafi\'i is widely credited as the first to systematize this science in his seminal work Ar-Risalah. It is indispensable because: (1) Without it, one cannot understand how Islamic law is derived — one can memorize rulings but not evaluate their evidence; (2) It distinguishes the mujtahid (independent scholar) from the muqallid (blind follower); (3) It provides the tools to address new situations (nawazil) not explicitly covered in classical texts; (4) It enables a scholar to weigh between conflicting evidences and reconcile apparent contradictions. Imam Al-Ghazali said in Al-Mustasfa: "The science of Usul Al-Fiqh is among the noblest, most elevated, most fruitful, and most important of the Islamic sciences." The Quran itself addresses this need: "Ask the people of knowledge if you do not know." (Quran 21:7) — establishing that not everyone can derive rulings directly, and those who can must understand the principles of derivation.',
