    id: 'usul_int_31',
    level: 'intermediate',
    discipline: 'usul',
    question: 'What is the concept of Ahkam Al-Wadiyyah related to As-Sabab Al-Khas in Islamic legal theory?',
    answer: 'Within the Hukm Al-Wad\'i framework, As-Sabab Al-Khas (the specific cause) is the particular identifiable trigger that brings a ruling into effect. Scholars distinguish: (1) As-Sabab Al-Khas — a particular time-bound event that triggers a ruling: the entry of Ramadan triggers fasting obligation; the completion of the Hijri year (hawl) on a nisab triggers zakah. (2) As-Sabab Al-\'Amm — a general ongoing condition. The relationship between sabab, shart, and mani\': they work together. Example for zakah: (a) Sabab: possessing nisab — ownership of the minimum amount is the cause; (b) Shart: hawl (passage of one lunar year) — the condition that must be met; (c) Mani\': debt — a debt equal to or exceeding the nisab is an impediment preventing the obligation. All three must be analyzed for every ruling. The importance for students: understanding why rulings activate and deactivate in different circumstances (e.g. why zakah is not due on jewelry in the Shafi\'i school but is due in the Hanafi school) requires understanding the scholars\' different analyses of sabab, shart, and mani\' for the same situation.',
